INTRODUCTION:

All living things on earth, as well as the ecosystems in which they coexist, are referred to as part of the biodiversity of the planet. It includes the genetic diversity within species, the diversity of ecosystems, and the ecological processes that support life. It also includes the diversity of species.

A variety of legal and policy tools have been used in the United Kingdom to take action to preserve biodiversity. The Wildlife and Countryside Act of 1981, which offers legal protection for numerous species and ecosystems, is one of the most crucial. A Biodiversity Action Plan, created by the UK government in 1994, describes methods for protecting biodiversity among various habitats and species.

Here, we use proportional_species_richness.csv to analyse species data, for data analysis and statistical analysis of biodiversity across Great Britain. These data represent a valuable resource for diversity of ecosystems based on ecological species value. We analyze species count and mean patterns of this data and apply the statistical analysis to consider the ecological status of species on land zones in Great Britain.

Hypothesis Testing:

  1. For all land zone in Scotland, it has shown increase in mean of ecological score of 7 species.

  • Null hypothesis: Ecological score in Scotland has not increased over time.

  • Alternative hypothesis: Ecological score in Scotland has increased over time.

The level of significance taken is 0.95

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  dff_in_eco_score_scotland$period_dff
## t = 3.8219, df = 15, p-value = 0.0008335
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.01506418        Inf
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## 0.02782915

Conclusion:
As the p-value is < 0.05, we reject the Null-Hypothesis thus proving that the ecological species richness has increased in Scotland over time.

  1. The BD7 for each dominantlandclass has increased over time from Y70 to Y00:

  • Null hypothesis: BD7 for each dominatlandclass has not increased over time.

  • Alternative hypothesis: BD7 for each dominatlandclass has increased over time.

The level of significance taken is 0.99

## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  best_eco_Y00$period_dff
## t = 8.0547, df = 44, p-value = 1.684e-10
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is greater than 0
## 99 percent confidence interval:
##  0.0289111       Inf
## sample estimates:
##  mean of x 
## 0.04128494

Conclusion:

As the p-value is < 0.05, we reject the Null-Hypothesis thus proving that the ecological species richness has increased over time.
